Massive data resources are coming online in every conceivable area of human exploration, and particularly in heavily observation-based fields such as astrophysics and astronomy. Striking advances in space-based instrumentation continuously increase the quality as well as the quantity of data available to astronomers. Enormous catalogs are being complied, and observations are made across the electromagnetic spectrum providing multi-domain astrophysical measurements. These include high-resolution, but heterogeneous spectrography, imaging, and time series. Efficient statistical and computational methods play an instrumental role in scientists' endeavors to use these rich yet complex data to understand the physical environment and structure of astronomical sources, the processes governing their birth and death, and ultimately the structure and evolution of the universe. The required analytic tools for such scientific quests typically involve subtle tradeoffs between complexity and practicality and pose significant computational challenges.  The CHASC International Center for Astrostatistics has a long record of building such tools to address such specific challenges, and of further developing them into general methodologies for solving problems in many other fields.

Specifically, this grant support has enabled the CHSAC team to

Establish      a new framework for formally detecting unspecified extended structure in      high-energy astrophysical images; &#8232; 
Develop      new methods to identify solar regions with similar thermal activity; &#8232;
Construct      classes of models for source disambiguation using multiple features; &#8232;
Prepare      software that is freely available.
Develop      principled methods that account for uncertainty in complex instrumental      calibration; 
Forecast      the evolutionary paths of solar active regions using new tracking and classification      techniques; &#8232;
Develop      new Monte Carlo methods for more efficient computation.


These research accomplishments have the dual impact of more reliable statistical methods on astronomy and of the new statistical inference and computation methods on other fields. In addition to provide methods and free software, the CHASC team also made extensive effort to communicate to the astronomical community about the benefit of principled statistical methods, through workshops and sessions at conferences. The general methods developed for efficient modeling of scientific phenomena, science-driven classification, clustering and segmentation, and for statistical computing, can also help to address complex data challenges throughout the natural, social, medical, and engineering sciences.



